recordings.rmk: Recording unmodified. This song was originally uploaded as Yellow-tailed Oriole but I see now that the song does not fit that species.  There was a lot of bird activity that morning. With several Oriole species in the vicinity. Any thoughts on what Oriole (or other type of bird) gave this song? Yellow-tailed, Baltimore and Orchard Orioles were in the area. Black-cowled Oriole is also known from the location. There are probably other candidates as well.   UPDATE:  Compare XC244358.  I believe this is probably the song of Baltimore oriole.

Philadelphia
recordings.rmk:
Bird Boy is an exploration of nature, chill beats created with bird calls. I met sound recordist Paul Marvin who had made some absolutely beautiful recordings of the Baltimore Oriole. 

My composition surrounds the notes the Oriole naturally sings, in its natural rhythm. I tried to do as little audio manipulation as possible for this one, so the Oriole's call sounds just as you would hear it in the wild.

I live in Philadelphia and have lots of friends in Baltimore, so this local bird has a bit of a personal connection. Thanks for listen, and I hope you enjoy

recordings.rmk: Fol xc277973 immediately after. More of the 2-noted call of male just before it relocated briefly to ground. Lark Sparrow song in background. Also note likely Lark Sparrow flyby with flight calls noted loudest between 18 and 20 seconds. Likely late-moving Myrtle Warbler chip at 24 secs- which was not in eBird list.

recordings.loc: 1 (near  Shreveport), Caddo Parish, Louisiana
recordings.rmk: Migrant or breeder. Interesting two-noted calls heard just after 0:2 at 0:10 0:12 and 0:15 observed given by adult male. Faint "trumpet call" also just after 0:19 Twenty two secs of bad wind clipped at intervals throughout from the original recording. Song heard just after beginning, then near end was given by another male perched nearby. Several birds seen in this small pecan orchard surrounded by plowed fields. The calling bird was also observed dropping briefly to the ground and foraging in the plowed field to north, before returning to the orchard.
